{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"66888190-5ff7-4ba4-bc39-22cafc64eaa2","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect the trace:**\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect for ~30 seconds (or Ctrl+C to stop)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **Speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**3. Copy out of the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't be installed (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or `dotnet-monitor` image instead.\n- For production, consider deploying [`dotnet-monitor`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP API to collect traces on demand without exec'ing in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c8680328-9eda-4f39-9926-201de7144abb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":409},"id":"4af84f28-8cc5-4796-9f07-215a9032569c","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:50.084Z","parentId":"aaeb6c25-fe40-44c5-8bbf-0a9d0a300195"}
